%I A393969 #16 Apr 03 2026 10:08:25
%S A393969 3,5,14,24,32,25,13,5,1
%N A393969 a(n) is the number of distinct n-edges, fully-dimensional incomplete open cubes (see Comments for precise definition).
%C A393969 Here, an incomplete open cube is a fully connected proper subset of the edges of a cube, with the additional requirement that each of the three coordinate directions is parallel to at least one edge of the object. Two configurations are considered identical if one can be obtained from the other by rotation.
%C A393969 The 122 resulting total configurations are the subject of Sol DeWitt's 1974 work "Incomplete Open Cubes".
%H A393969 Paul Dancstep, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_BrFKp-U8GI">Exploration & Epiphany</a>, 3Blue1Brown YouTube video, 2025.
%H A393969 Sol DeWitt, <a href="https://www.sfmoma.org/artwork/97.516.A-KKKKKKKKKK/">Incomplete Open Cubes, 1974</a>, San Francisco Museum of Modern Art.
%H A393969 Alison Pitt, <a href="https://www.alisonpitt.com/blog/an-exploration-of-incomplete-open-cubes">An Exploration of Incomplete Open Cubes</a>, 2023.
%H A393969 Natasha Rozhkovskaya and Michael Reb, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/s00004-015-0254-8">Is the List of Incomplete Open Cubes Complete?</a>, Nexus Network Journal, Volume 17, 2015, pp. 913-925.
